data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Core Problem

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core+. The idiomatic replacement is `CancellationToken` with `Task`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to preserve original behavior
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    // Async-first overload (preferred)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort` is gone** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. No replacement exists for forcibly killing threads. |
| **Cancellation is cooperative** | The `work` delegate **must** check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass the token to I/O APIs. Unlike `Abort()`, uncooperative code **won't stop**. |
| **Signature change is breaking** | `Func<T>` → `Func<CancellationToken, T>`. All callers must be updated. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool** | The original code created a dedicated thread. Long-running CPU work may starve the pool. Use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)` if needed. |
| **Exception unwrapping differs** | `Task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` throws the inner exception directly (not wrapped in `AggregateException`), unlike the original which explicitly wrapped. Callers catching `AggregateException` need updating. |
| **`WaitAsync` (.NET 6+)** | The async overload uses `WaitAsync` to enforce the timeout even if the inner task ignores cancellation — the caller unblocks, though the orphaned task keeps running. |

### Caller Migration Example

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => SlowComputation(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (.NET 8) — work must observe the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // check periodically
        DoChunkOfWork(i);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**Bottom line:** There is no drop-in replacement for `Thread.Abort`. Cancellation in .NET 8 is *cooperative* — the migrated work delegates must actively check the `CancellationToken`, or they will run to completion regardless of the timeout.
